Thai police on Friday moved to request an arrest warrant for an heir to the Red Bull energy drink fortune accused of a deadly hit-and-run incident nearly five years ago.The Thai public is watching whether the court will issue an arrest warrant for Vorayuth "Boss" Yoovidhya, whose repeated ability to avoid police summons has come to symbolize the impunity of the rich and connected."The prosecutors have decided to no longer allow Vorayuth to seek another delay. This has dragged on for too long and it has affected the attorney general's image," said Somnuk Siangkong, spokesman for the office of the attorney general.Yoovidhya was 27-years-old when in 2012 his Ferrari allegedly crashed into a motorcycle police in Bangkok, killing the rider.Read: Thai king signs military-backed constitutionSome of the minor accusations against him have since expired. Yoovidhya denies reckless driving accusations, saying the police officer veered in front of him. Authorities have until 2027 to pursue those charges. Another hit-and-run offense is valid until September.Thai police inspect the Ferrari of alleged hit-and-run suspect Vorayuth Yoovidhya For nearly five years Yoovidhya has failed to show up to summons on several occasions, doing so again on Thursday. Yoovidhya's&nbsp;attorney has repeated said his client was unable to attend summons due to business or other activities out of the country.Thursday's failure to show up to another summons appeared to be the final straw, prompting&nbsp;prosecutors to ask police to request an arrest warrant from a court.Police must submit the request to a court, which then decides whether to issue a warrant."He will turn into an individual who is evading an arrest warrant like in any other case," national police chief Gen. Chaktip Chaijinda.Yoovidhya has moved in and out of Thailand. He was last seen in London in early April.The Attorney-General's office said that if Yoovidhya is not arrested in Thailand they will seek his extradition. Thailand and the UK have an extradition treaty.Read: Man in Thailand kills baby on Facebook LiveVorayuth's grandfather Chaleo Yoovidhya co-founded Red Bull with Austrian Dietrich Mateschitz in the 1980s.After Chaleo died in 2012, he left 11 relatives a fortune estimated at nearly 18 billion euros ($20 billion).cw/rt&nbsp;(AP, dpa, Reuters)